  institution = {The Johns Hopkins University},
  abstract = {Motivation: Biomolecular pathways consist of non-random network motifs that establish the circuitry of evolved functions. Few studies have analyzed the network motifs of pathogens to develop virulence and infectivity models. In addition, databases lack comprehensive interaction data and over-represent model organisms. Accordingly, a recently introduced algorithm generated de novo co-expression networks directly from microarray data. The combinatorial nature of the algorithm required a parallel implementation to significantly re- duce runtime. This investigation re-implements the algorithm to further reduce runtime in order to analyze a greater percentage of probes from microarray experiments involving Yersinia pestis, an emerging infectious pathogen that threatens human populations via zoonoses and potential bioterror attacks. Subsequent network motif analysis identifies key interaction patterns and proteins in pathways critical to pathogenicity. The resulting pipeline and model facilitates the design of proactive countermeasures against potential out- breaks. Results: The investigation yielded a parallel implementation of the co-expression network generation algorithm that achieves runtimes that are inversely proportional to the number of processes. However, the thresholds to add edges and remove false positives result in networks with too many edges for analysis. Subsequent experimen- tation with other threshold routines and additional microarrays may rectify the problem. Nevertheless, there is potential to include an entire microarray probe set with the current communication frame- work or on an alternate system with globally addressable memory. Contact: dnegron1@jhu.edu or Daniel.Negron@noblis.org},
  file = {/Users/dnanto/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-GeorgeMasonUniversity-O365Production/Zotero/negrón_2011_parallel_algorithm_for_de_novo_co-expression_networks_from_microarray_data.pdf}
